  <entry>
    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Java + Programmation fonctionnelle + Funky = FunkyJFunctional !]]></title>
    <link href="http://www.web-tambouille.fr/2011/04/05/java-plus-programmation-fonctionnelle-plus-funky-egal-funkyjfunctional.html"/>
    <updated>2011-04-05T00:00:00+02:00</updated>
    <id>http://www.web-tambouille.fr/2011/04/05/java-plus-programmation-fonctionnelle-plus-funky-egal-funkyjfunctional</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://picasaweb.google.com/lh/photo/nMrNHG_1l1y3WohchX2EKA?feat=embedwebsite"><img style="float: right; margin: 10px;" src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-Il3aKnteYJY/ThmqRC_eSXI/AAAAAAAAAuk/d1gwQ4AkEeY/s800/logo_programmation_fonctionnelle.jpg" alt="Programmation Fonctionnelle" width="100" height="100" /></a>Courant de semaine derni&egrave;re, alors que je faisais un important refactoring pour am&eacute;liorer la lisibilit&eacute; du code, je suis tomb&eacute; sur une librairie au nom assez rigolo : <a href="https://github.com/pyricau/FunkyJFunctional" target="_blank">FunkyJFunctional</a>. Comme je suis un <em>Funky d&eacute;veloppeur</em> <img title="Laughing" src="http://www.web-tambouille.fr/tinymce/plugins/emoticons/img/smiley-laughing.gif" border="0" alt="Laughing" />&nbsp;j'ai regard&eacute; de plus pr&egrave;s...</p>


<p>Comme vous le savez peut-&ecirc;tre d&eacute;j&agrave;, j'aime beaucoup la <a href="http://web-tambouille.fr/2011/01/11/programmation-fonctionnelle-en-javascript.html" target="_blank">programmation fonctionnelle</a> et le langage <a href="http://blog.xebia.fr/author/rmaton/" target="_blank">Scala</a>. Et, sur ce refactoring qui concernait &agrave; la fois du code m&eacute;tier mais aussi des tests <em>(tout &ccedil;a en Java)</em>, j'ai pu mettre en oeuvre et utiliser de mani&egrave;re pouss&eacute;e des librairies comme <a href="http://code.google.com/p/guava-libraries/" target="_blank">Google Guava</a>, <a href="http://code.google.com/p/fest/#Fluent_Assertions" target="_blank">Fest-Assert</a> ou bien encore <a href="http://mockito.org/" target="_blank">Mockito</a> et plus particuli&egrave;rement son package <a href="http://docs.mockito.googlecode.com/hg/org/mockito/BDDMockito.html" target="_blank">BDDMockito</a>&nbsp;<em>(pour faire du given-when-then)</em>. Cela pourra d'ailleurs faire l'objet d'un prochain article avec un exemple de code avant-apr&egrave;s, le r&eacute;sultat est assez bluffant.</p>


<p>Bien s&ucirc;r, ce n'est pas encore du DSL comme <a href="http://www.scalatest.org/" target="_blank">on peut en voir en Scala</a> mais &agrave; l'aide de quelques astuces syntaxiques, ces librairies nous offrent une API&nbsp;<em>fluent</em> qui permet r&eacute;ellement de <em>lire</em> du code comme si nous lisions une phrase. Ceci est un aspect tr&egrave;s important surtout pour les tests qui pour moi reste la documentation principale du code d'une application.</p>


<p>Et donc, pour pousser encore plus loin ce concept de lisibilit&eacute;, voici une petite librairie qui simplifie encore plus <em>(oui oui)</em> certaines API Java <em>(Runnable, Comparator)</em>, Google Guava<em>,</em> Swing et m&ecirc;me Wicket ! Alors, le Funky qui est en vous est int&eacute;ress&eacute; ?</p>


<p><!--more--></p>


<h3>Pr&eacute;sentation</h3>


<p>FunkyJFunctional est une librairie Java qui va nous permettre de coder de mani&egrave;re fonctionnelle. Java n'est bien s&ucirc;r pas un langage fonctionnelle mais ce concept peut &ecirc;tre &eacute;mul&eacute; gr&acirc;ce &agrave; certaines astuces du langage. Des librairies comme Google Guava utilisent le concept de classe anonyme avec la d&eacute;finition d'un objet directement depuis une interface <em>(<span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Predicate&lt;T&gt;</span>, <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Function&lt;F, T&gt;</span>...)</em>&nbsp;telle que :</p>


<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='java'><span class='line'><span class="n">Iterable</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Integer</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">evenNumbers</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Iterables</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">filter</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">numbers</span><span class="o">,</span> <span class="k">new</span> <span class="n">Predicate</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Integer</span><span class="o">&gt;()</span> <span class="o">{</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="nd">@Override</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="kd">public</span> <span class="kt">boolean</span> <span class="nf">apply</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">Integer</span> <span class="n">number</span><span class="o">)</span> <span class="o">{&lt;/</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">pre</span><span class="o">&gt;&lt;</span><span class="n">code</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>  <span class="k">return</span> <span class="o">(</span><span class="n">number</span> <span class="o">%</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="o">)</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="o">;</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">&lt;/</span><span class="n">code</span><span class="o">&gt;&lt;/</span><span class="n">pre</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>   <span class="o">}</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">});</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<p>FunkyJFunctional s'appuie lui sur le m&eacute;canisme des <a href="http://java.sun.com/docs/books/jls/second_edition/html/statements.doc.html#247766" target="_blank">classes internes locales</a> coupl&eacute;es au <a href="http://download.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/initial.html" target="_blank">bloc d'initialisation d'instanc</a>e. Et oui tout &ccedil;a <img title="Smile" src="http://www.web-tambouille.fr/tinymce/plugins/emoticons/img/smiley-smile.gif" border="0" alt="Smile" />&nbsp;et le r&eacute;sultat et assez surprenant puisque notre exemple ci-dessus devient :</p>


<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='java'><span class='line'><span class="kd">class</span> <span class="nc">Even</span> <span class="kd">extends</span> <span class="n">Pred</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Integer</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="n">Iterable</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Integer</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">evens</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Iterables</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">filter</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">numbers</span><span class="o">,</span> <span class="n">FunkyGuava</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">withPred</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">Even</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">class</span><span class="o">));</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<p>Cette &eacute;criture rappelle bien &eacute;videmment la&nbsp;<a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/15496/hidden-features-of-java" target="_blank"><em>hidden feature</em>&nbsp;n&deg;1 de Java</a>&nbsp;&agrave; savoir le&nbsp;<a href="http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?DoubleBraceInitialization" target="_blank"><em>double brace initialization</em></a>. Au final :&nbsp;plus besoin de passer par une classe anonyme qui descend une m&eacute;thode <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">apply</span>, nous avons directement des variables pr&eacute;d&eacute;finies <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">r</span> et <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">t</span> qui nous permettent d'&eacute;crire directement notre code m&eacute;tier souhait&eacute;. On a ainsi, &agrave; la lecture, le code m&eacute;tier qui saute aux yeux &agrave; savoir <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">r = t % 2</span> qui rappelle bien s&ucirc;r ce que l'on peut voir dans d'autres langages fonctionnels <em>(par exemple avec Scala <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">x =&gt; x % 2</span>)</em>.</p>


<p>Il est possible de d&eacute;finir ces classes <em>Funky</em>&nbsp;sur des :</p>


<ul>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Runnable</span> et <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Comparator</span>&nbsp;de Java,</li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Predicate,</span>&nbsp;<span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Function, Constraint<span style="font-family: 'Lucida Grande', 'Lucida Sans Unicode', Tahoma, Verdana, sans-serif;">&nbsp;et </span>Supplier</span>&nbsp;de Google Guava,&nbsp;</li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">ActionListener</span>&nbsp;de Swing,</li>
<li><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">AbstractReadOnlyModel</span>&nbsp;de Wicket.</li>
</ul>


<p>Nous allons surtout regarder du c&ocirc;t&eacute; de Java et Google Guava.</p>


<h3>Installation</h3>


<p>Les jars se t&eacute;l&eacute;chargent ici, il vous suffit de r&eacute;cup&eacute;rer <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">core</span> et ensuite de choisir les jars des modules dont vous avez besoin :&nbsp;<a href="https://github.com/pyricau/FunkyJFunctional/tree/master/releases/info/piwai/funkyjfunctional" target="_blank">https://github.com/pyricau/FunkyJFunctional/tree/master/releases/info/piwai/funkyjfunctional</a></p>


<p>Et si vous utilisez maven, vous pouvez ajouter ce repository ainsi que cette d&eacute;pendance pour b&eacute;n&eacute;ficier de la libraire, de m&ecirc;me les d&eacute;pendances correspondront aux modules que vous souhaitez utiliser &nbsp;:</p>


<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
<span class='line-number'>12</span>
<span class='line-number'>13</span>
<span class='line-number'>14</span>
<span class='line-number'>15</span>
<span class='line-number'>16</span>
<span class='line-number'>17</span>
<span class='line-number'>18</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='java'><span class='line'><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">repositories</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">repository</span><span class="o">&gt;&lt;/</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
